    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-05-18T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-05-18T14:00:00-05:00" n="184"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d184">
                <head>184. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Delegation at the Summit
                        Conference</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d184fn0">Source: Department of State,
                        Conference Files: Lot 64 D 559, <gloss target="#t_CF1">CF</gloss> 1666.
                        Confidential. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MSJM1">McSweeney</persName>
                        and authorized by <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName>. Repeated to
                        London, Moscow, and Bonn.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Paris</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1960-05-18T20:00:00+01:00">May 18, 1960, 8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 38. According to French official source
                        <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> farewell call on <persName
                        corresp="#p_dGC1">De Gaulle</persName>, accompanied by <persName
                        corresp="#p_MMRY1">Malinovsky</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                        >Gromyko</persName>, lasted 45 minutes.<note n="1" xml:id="d184fn1">A
                        memorandum of <persName corresp="#p_BCE1">Bohlen</persName>’s conversation
                        with <persName corresp="#p_dCGC1">de Courcel</persName> (US/<gloss
                            target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>/19), from which this summary was made, is <hi
                            rend="italic">ibid</hi>., <gloss target="#t_CF1">CF</gloss> 1664.
                            <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> made the call during
                        the morning of May 18.</note> Tone was calm and courteous. <persName
                        corresp="#p_dGC1">De Gaulle</persName> raised no matters of substance.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> reiterated position on
                    non-attendance Summit with harsh criticism of President <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> in relation to airplane incident
                    which made Summit impossible and set back policies <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName> had been working on. Particularly regretted Summit
                    breakdown as regards disarmament since he had been prepared present many
                    “constructive” proposals which would now be submitted to 10-nation group at
                    Geneva. No mention was made of Berlin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
